h 1908 tn Rtockholders of record at\nfhe cinse of business April 32, 190<\nFRED F CHAMBERS.\nRecretary Treasurer\nTHE CITIZENS CFNT\u00ae AL NATIONAL BANK OF\nNew ore, March 20, 180k\nThe Board of Directors has thic day deciared a divi\nfend of ONE AXD ONE-HALF PER CEXT free of\ntex, out of the earrings of the nas: three months. pa:\ngable or and 2fter Anril Ist. 189% to stockholders of\nrecord 2t the cisse of business March 27th, 1968\nALRION K CHAPMAN, Cashier\nTHE NEW YORK AND NEW JERSEY TELEPHONE\nCOMPANY,\n\u00a31 Willoughby Sree: Rrooklyn, N.Y.\nDIVIDEND NO 88\nA regular quartesiy dividend of one and three quarters\nrent has heen declared an the capi 2] stack of this\nBr. payable Apri] THhth, 180% +a stockholders of\nrecor; at the close of bosiress Aprii 4th 1008\nFORD HI'XTINGTON \"Treasures\n\u00abAEN ICT XHaAa'TD 4 TNR\nThe Board of Directors has thic day declared a divi\nfend of ONE AXD ONE-HALF PER CEXT free of\ntex, out of the earrings of the nas: three months, pav\ngable or and zfter Anril Ist. 1898 to stockholders of\nrecord 2t the close of business March 27th, 190K\nALRINON K. CHAPMAN. Cashier\nTHE INION BAG PAPER COMPANY.\nB8th Oeartesriy Nividend\n17 Dartery Piace, New York City, March 10th, 190%\nA quarteriv dividend of ONE PER CEXT. on the pre.\nwere\u201d atl: of The Union Rag Taper Company has\nthis day heen declared, payable April 15. 19K 10 stock\nhiniflers of reccrd at the close of business on March 14th,\nae\nThe transfer books will be closed at twelve o'clock M.,\non March 12h, 15%, and reopen at ten o'clek A M.,\n\u00a9on April 16th. 19K WwW 1. SPARKS. Secretary.\nGARBRFIFEID NATIONAL BANK\n4weniy-iharc SR. ag TIXIn Ave\nNew York, March 20. 1008\nAt 3 meeting of the Board of Directors of this Bank.\nSed this dav. 2 auarterly dividend of THREE PER\nCERT was declared on the casita! stock of this bank,\ngavable fres of 23 on and after March 2is:, 190%\nThe Trans\u2019<r Books will he closed until Wedinesday,\nArti 1.0, 1805\nIL. DOUGLASS, Cashier.\nHE FOURT NATIONAL BANK OF THE CITY OF\nNew York New York, March 17. 1908 Tone\nBoard of Digertors has this day declares a quarteriy\nLividend of TWO PER CEN payable on and after\nApril ist proxime The transfer books will closs at 3\nP NM this Sste, reopening April Ist 150K\nCHARLES H PATTERSON, Cashier\nDYERTISEMENTS a: subscri~ ions for The Tribune\n22 rereived gt thelr Uptown Of ce. No. 1264 Broadway,\ntetawen 6th and Eth tx until orlock p m Adver\ngisements =c_.ved at the fallowing Ddranch offices at\ngegular o7 os rates urtil 8 cociock pW viz M1 Sh\n&ve e cor. 234 st; 183 8th gve cor. 12th st. 92 Fast\nJerr ot; 257 Wee: 424 51. .ween 7th nd Sih aves\na\nI I I) I TE IA ay\neral days in an unusually large number of\nclosed with net for\nthe great majority of stocks in which there had\nbeen dealings. Unlike the preceding week, when\nthe improvement had ,.actically been confined\nto the industrial group, the railroads also cams\nin for a full share in the gains, although the net\nadvances in a number of the most prominent\nrailroad stocks, among them Union Pacific;\nSouthern Pacific, Reading, Northern Pacific and\nAtchison, were less than two points each. The\ntrading was still in the main professional. but\nthe steady movement of prices toward a higher\nlevel seemed to have had the effect of bringing\nin outside buvers to some extent. a moderate in\ncrease in commission house business being re\nported. The earliest and most important bullish\ninfluence of the week was without doubt the\nseries of opinions handed down by the Supreme\nCourt on Monday in cases affecting railroads in\nMinnesota and North Carolina. It need hardly\nbe pointed out how great hardship has been\nworked upon railroads in many states by the\nlegislation enthusiastically enacted during the\nheight of the anti-railroad sentiment of the last\nyear or two and how serious has been the re\nsulting apprehension aroused in the minds of\nrailroad managers and of investors, and it Is not\neasy to overestimate the beneficial influence of\nthe Supreme Court's decisions, interposing as\nthey do an effective check to oppressive and\nconfiscatory legislation and assuring equitable\ntreatment f transportation corporations by the\nstates in which their lines are operated. In\nmany quarters the Supreme Court's action in\nthe railroad cases is believed to foreshadow a\nreversal of the $29,000,000 fine imposed on the\nStandard Oil Company of Indiana by Judge\nLandis when that case shall reach the court of\nlast resort.\nThe President's special message sent to Con\ngress last week also produced an excellent im\npression, from the manner in which he pre\nsented and discussed the legislation suggested by\nhin. even among those who are not in accord\nwith him as to the desirability of the changes\nadvocated. The passage of the Aldrich bill hy\nthe Senate, with the prospect of similar action\nbr the House within a short time and the en\nactment ~f the measure into law, had some\nslightly beneficial effect on the market, al\nthough the bill, which was at neo time caleu\nlated io effect a real reform of the country\u2019s\ncurrency systenr, has now been so amended zs\nto have lost most of the value which it may\noriginally have possessed. More important than\nthe action on the Aldrich bill in its good effect\non sentiment was the resumption of business by\nthe Knickerbocker Trust Compan), as the out\ncome of some months of unremitting effort, in\nwhich many serious obstacles were met and\novercome. for the rehabilitation of that great in\nstitution could not have been effected without\nthe co-operation of the thousands of depositors,\nthe giving of which has been a significant indi\ncation of the revival of confidence in the per\nmanence of the improvement in the general sit\nuation.\nEasy conditions continue to prevail in the\nmoney market, call loans commanding no higher\nrate than 2 per cent, as for many weeks past,\nand time funds being obtainable at low rates\nfor all maturities, the demand for money being\n\nlizht that borrowers still incline to fiil thelr\nrequirements by call loans, seeing little indica\ntion of a stiffening of rates for the present. The\nmovement of funds from the intericr has not\nceased, and is so large that, despite the return\nwithin the last few weeks of $35,000,000 of the\ngovernment's special deposits, the greater part\nof which was forwarded from this centre. the\nAccociated Banks of New York now hold about\n$40.000 000 of cash in excess of the 25 per cent\nreserve required by the Clearing House of its\nmembers. So great is the plethora of money\nhere. reflected in the low money rates, that gold\n\u00a2xporis might be looked for were it not that\nsimilar ease, resulting from similar lack of\nprofitable employment for money, prevails in\nEurope The federal Treasury, which at the\nbeginning of the year had only about 23.000,000\nfree cash, now has a working balance of $54.\n770.000, a sum in excess of that usually main\ntained by it in this fund. Iis deposits in na\ntional banks. which can be recalled on demand.\nare stil! in excess of $182,000,6060, and with the\nincrease of the national deficit another heavy\nwithdrawal is likely before the end of the fiscal\nvear, a call which the banks will be able to meet\nwithout serinrus impairment of the strength of\ntheir positien.\n\n\n\n\n\nThe reports of the great mercantile agencies\nconcur in the statement that gradual improve\nment in business and indusiry is noticeable, al\nthough it is no more than gradual and shows\nmuch irregularity. In the textile industries the\n\ncurtailment of production continues, and the buy\nine. while fairly brisk, represents chiefly a de\nmand for the replenishing of depleted stocks. The\nimprovement in the iron and steel industry noted\nin the annual report of the United States Steel\nCorporation appears to have been haited, and,\nalthough the business being done is on a much\nlarger scale than at the opening cf the year, an\napproach to normal production can hardly he\nexpected until conditions shall have so decidedly\nimproved that the railroads will be enabled to\nobtain at favorable rates the funds with which\nto pay for heavy orders of rails and otter ma\nterial In the copper industry the outlock now\nseems better, the domestic consumers, who had\nlong held aloof, being reported as purchasers of\nthe metal to so large an extent as to bring the\nstocks down to low proportions. While a more\nhopeful feeling is evident in the business world,\nthe recovery from the effects of the panic must\nbe expected to be a slow process.\n\nCommercial failures are still abundant, those\nof iast week being larger in number than in the\npreceding week, and railroad earnings show se\nvere falling off from the corresponding period of\n1307. althcugh the shrinkages are a little less\nthan reported in the earlier weeks of the cur\nrent year, while the returns of bank clearings\ntell the story of diminished trade activity. It is\nearly vet for crop forerasts, but the indications\nthus far presented point to harvests of normal\nsize, the garnering of which would be a factor\nof the highest value in effecting a return of\nprosperity for the country. The political situa\ntion is still invalved, and until it shall clear to\nsome extent and until it shall be possible to\nknow with a fair degree of certainty what the\nvield of corn and wheat and cotton is to be\nthere is not likely to he any definite step for\nward toward the re-establishment of that\nabounding prosperity which the country enjoved\nvear ago, and which it will enjoy in added\nmeasure in the not far distant future\n\n\nThe decision of the Union Pacific's directors\nlast week to ask the stockholders to authorize a\nlarge bond issue was from one point of view well\nreceived by the Street, as indicating the opinion\nof the prominent financiers in that board that\nthe market could absorb a large bond issue. In\nother directions, though, it met with much\neriticism, in which was brought up again the\n\n\nBR BE AR ns A Rs Rud er Mist Bll Le SB ae Br M0\nCorporation appears to have been haited, and,\nalthough the business being done is on a much\nlarger scale than at the opening of the year, an\napproach to normal production can hardly be\nexpected until conditions shall have so decidedly\nimproved that the railroads will be enabled to\nobtain at favorable rates the funds with which\nto pay for heavy orders of rails and otHer ma\nterial In the copper industry the outlock now\nseems better. the domestic consumers, who had\nlong held aloof, being reported as purchasers of\nthe metal to so large an extent as to bring the\nstocks down to low proportions. While a more\nhopeful feeling is evident in the business world,\nthe recovery from the effects of the panic must\nbe expected to be a slow process.\nCommercial failures are still abundant, those\nof iast week being larger in number than in the\npreceding week, and railroad earnings show se\nvere falling off from the corresponding period of\n1307. althcugh the shrinkages are a little less\nthan reported in the earlier weeks of the cur\nrent year, while the returns of bank clearings\ntell the story of diminished trade activity. It is\nearly vet for crop forervasts, but the indications\nthus far presented point to harvests of normal\nsize, the garnering of which would be a factor\nof the highest value in effecting a return of\nprosperity for the country. The political situa\ntion is still invalved, and until it shall clear to\nsome extent and until it shall be possible to\nknow with a fair degree of certainty what the\nvield of corn and wheat and cotton is to be\nthere iz not likely to be any definite step for\nward toward the re-establishment of that\nabounding prosperity which the country enjoved\nvear ago, and which it will enjoy in added\nmeasure in the not far distant future\nThe decision of the Union Pacific's directors\nlast week to ask the stockholders to authorize a\nlarge bond issue was from one point of view well\nreceived by the Street, as indicating the opinion\nof the prominent financiers in that board that\nthe market could absorb a large bond issue. In\nother directions, though, it met with much\neriticism, in which was brought up again the\nquestion of the soundness of the policy of the\ncompany making investments in millions upon\nmillions of securities of other roads, somne of\nthem far {rayn Union Pacific territory, these in\nvestments representing at present levels a loss\nof many millions of dollars to the Union Pacific\nand being to a considerable extent the cceasion\ning cause of the company\u2019s floating debt, to tha\nextinction of which a large part of the pro\nceeds of the new bond issue will be applied.\nThe vindication given by the board to the di\nrectors who sold stock of some of these other\nroads to the Union Pacific surprised no one.\nA significant and encouraging occurrence of\nihe week was the publication of the first annual\nreport of the American Sugar Refining Com\npany, which marked the abandonment of the\npolicy of secrecy to which the late President\nHavemever had alwavs been committed, Many\nimportant features usually to be found in an\nnual reports, such as the showing of gross\ni\n\nTHE FINANCIAL MARKETS.\n4 BROADENING STOCK LIST, WITH GENERAL AD\nVANCES DURING THE WEEK\nMoney Mar\nSome Public Interest Apparent\u2014The Railroad Decisions\nLet's Continued Ease\u2014Conditions Improving.\nTHE FINANCIAL MARKETS.\n4 BROADENING STOCK LIST, WITH GENERAL AD\nVANCES DURING THE WEEK.\nSome Public Interest Apparent\u2014T he Railroad Decisions\u2014Money Mar\nLet's Continued Ease\u2014Conditions Improving.\nTHE WEEK IN WALL STREET.\nThe stock market showed signs of broaden\nNEW-YORK DAILY TRIBUNE, MONDAY, MARCH 30, 1908.\nearnings and operating expenses, are omitted\nfrom this document, but the {issuance of the\nstatement at all marks an important step toward\ngeneral publicity for corporation